I think the ordering of the types isn't important here.  The fix works for the specific case but not the general one.  It also means the quickfixes offered for the following two classes are different:

// X.java
public class Y{}
public class Z{}

Checking in 3.3M7, swapping the lines and repeating the steps in comment 0 produces the same result, i.e. try:

// X.java
public class Y{}  // Quick fix RCU here + steps
public class X{}

It probably makes sense not to offer the quickfix if a public type corresponding to the file name (or a Unicode escape of it) already exists in the source, but that in itself won't fix this bug..

I also see the same problem with:

// X.java
class X{}
public class Y{}  // Quick fix RCU here + steps

and most of the symptoms with:

// X.java
public class Y{}  // Quick fix RCU here + steps
class Y{}

// X.java
public class Y{}  // Quick fix RCU here + steps

To clarify, the problems are:
 - Renaming CU X.java to Y.java via quick fix also renames type X to Y even if type Y is already declared in the CU.
 - Undoing the quick fix doesn't change the source back and causes subsequent operations (e.g. renaming back to X.java) to fail with errors in the log.

Reopening and renaming summary since the issue isn't just with multiple public types.
